  "market_context": "ETH on the 3-minute chart with 30-minute candles overlaid. Price is in a bearish move consolidating after a decline. The analyst waits for the consolidation lows to be swept before considering a long via inversion fair value gap.",
  "key_observation": "The candle that sweeps the consolidation lows opens, trades higher first, then expands lower — a bearish candle with a large opposing run, not a small wick supporting immediate expansion. Therefore the expansion needs to wait for the next higher-timeframe candle open.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify bearish move and consolidation; wait for consolidation lows to be taken out before looking for a long.",
    "Observe the previous candle's low gets swept, opening the possibility for an IFVG long setup.",
    "Examine the sweeping candle: it does not have a small wick at the low supporting expansion; instead it opens, runs higher, then expands lower — a bearish candle.",
    "Conclude expansion will not happen immediately; expect a return toward opening price forming a reversal candle.",
    "Mark the inversion zone as the two fair value gaps added together as the point of interest.",
    "Wait for a closure through that IFVG area as confirmation of the inversion.",
    "Take entry on the open of the next higher timeframe candle rather than on the closure, placing stop into the fair value gap.",
    "Target the other side of the range, 2R, or look for a continuation entry on the next IFVG/CISD."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price closed through the IFVG, delivered the expected continuation, and reached into another fair value gap with closure over — illustrating both a viable reversal entry and a continuation entry.",
  "lessons": "When a candle has a large opposing run (no small wick supporting expansion), the expansion typically waits for the next higher-timeframe candle open. Enter on the new candle open with stop inside the FVG, rather than chasing the closure.",
